(1) Recognition: tearing chest/back pain, BP/pulse asymmetry, mediastinal widening, AR murmur, neurologic deficit, malperfusion, syncope.

(2) Imaging: CT angiography (gold standard if stable), TEE (intraoperative or unstable), MRA. D-dimer high sensitivity but not diagnostic alone.

(3) Type A management: emergent surgical repair (replacement of ascending aorta ± valve ± arch ± aortic root); untreated mortality 1-2%/hr first 48 hr.

(4) Type B management: - Uncomplicated: medical therapy alone — beta-blocker + ACEi long-term, BP < 130/80. - Complicated (malperfusion, rupture, refractory pain, rapid expansion): TEVAR (thoracic endovascular aortic repair) — INSTEAD trial.

